üéì Exam Questions & Answers
Q1: What is @RestController?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Combination of @Controller + @ResponseBody
‚Ä¢	Automatically converts return values to JSON
‚Ä¢	Used for building REST APIs
‚Ä¢	No need to use @ResponseBody on each method
Q2: Difference between @Controller and @RestController?
@Controller	@RestController
Returns view name (HTML)	Returns data (JSON/XML)
Used with @ResponseBody	@ResponseBody included
For MVC apps	For REST APIs
Returns String ‚Üí view	Returns String ‚Üí JSON
Q3: What is ResponseEntity?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Represents entire HTTP response (status, headers, body)
‚Ä¢	Allows setting HTTP status codes
‚Ä¢	More control over response
Example:
java
return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.OK).body(student);
return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND).body("Not found");
Q4: What are @RequestBody and @PathVariable?
@RequestBody:
‚Ä¢	Binds HTTP request body to Java object
‚Ä¢	Used in POST, PUT methods
‚Ä¢	Example: @PostMapping public void add(@RequestBody Student student)
@PathVariable:
‚Ä¢	Extracts values from URI path
‚Ä¢	Used in GET, PUT, DELETE with IDs
‚Ä¢	Example: @GetMapping("/{id}") public Student get(@PathVariable int id)
Q5: What is @Service annotation?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Marks class as Service layer (business logic)
‚Ä¢	Detected by component scanning
‚Ä¢	Enables dependency injection
‚Ä¢	Separates business logic from controller
Q6: Why use Service layer?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Separation of Concerns - Controller handles HTTP, Service handles logic
‚Ä¢	Reusability - Service methods can be used by multiple controllers
‚Ä¢	Testability - Easy to test business logic independently
‚Ä¢	Maintainability - Changes to logic don't affect controller
Q7: What HTTP methods are used for CRUD?
Operation	HTTP Method	Example
Create	POST	Register student
Read	GET	View students
Update	PUT	Update student
Delete	DELETE	Delete student
Q8: What is the purpose of @RequestMapping?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Maps HTTP requests to controller methods
‚Ä¢	Can be at class level (base path) and method level
‚Ä¢	Example: @RequestMapping("/students") at class level
Q9: Explain the architecture of this application.
Answer:
Client (Postman)
    ‚Üì
REST Controller (@RestController)
    ‚Üì
Service Layer (@Service)
    ‚Üì
Data Storage (In-Memory List)
Layers:
1.	Controller - Handles HTTP requests/responses
2.	Service - Business logic and data manipulation
3.	Storage - In-memory ArrayList (can be replaced with database)
Q10: What is @Autowired?
Answer:
‚Ä¢	Enables automatic dependency injection
‚Ä¢	Spring creates and injects required objects
‚Ä¢	No need to manually create objects
‚Ä¢	Example: @Autowired private StudentService studentService;
Q11: How to test REST API without Postman?
Answer: You can use:
‚Ä¢	cURL (command line)
bash
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/students \
       -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
       -d '{"studentId":101,"name":"John",...}'
‚Ä¢	Browser (for GET only)
‚Ä¢	Swagger UI
‚Ä¢	JUnit tests
Q12: What is the difference between PUT and POST?
POST	PUT
Create new resource	Update existing resource
Not idempotent	Idempotent
/students	/students/{id}
Returns 201 Created	Returns 200 OK
Q13: Why use in-memory storage instead of database?
Answer: Advantages:
‚Ä¢	‚úÖ Simple and fast for learning/testing
‚Ä¢	‚úÖ No database setup required
‚Ä¢	‚úÖ No configuration needed
‚Ä¢	‚úÖ Quick prototyping
Disadvantages:
‚Ä¢	‚ùå Data lost on restart
‚Ä¢	‚ùå Not suitable for production
‚Ä¢	‚ùå No persistence
For production: Replace ArrayList with database (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)
Q14: How to add database instead of in-memory storage?
Answer:
1.	Add dependencies (spring-boot-starter-data-jpa, mysql-connector)
2.	Add @Entity, @Id to Student.java
3.	Create StudentRepository extends JpaRepository
4.	Configure database in application.properties
5.	Use repository in service instead of ArrayList
Q15: What is the flow when POST request is made?
Answer:
1.	Client sends POST request with JSON body
2.	Spring converts JSON to Student object (@RequestBody)
3.	Controller receives Student object
4.	Controller calls studentService.registerStudent()
5.	Service adds student to ArrayList
6.	Service returns student object
7.	Controller creates ResponseEntity with status 201
8.	Spring converts response to JSON
9.	Client receives JSON response with status code
________________________________________
üêõ Troubleshooting
Issue 1: Application won't start
Error: Port 8080 is already in use
Solution: Change port in application.properties:
properties
server.port=8081
Issue 2: 404 Not Found for all endpoints
Solution:
‚Ä¢	Ensure base URL is correct: http://localhost:8080/students
‚Ä¢	Check @RestController and @RequestMapping are present
‚Ä¢	Verify application started successfully
Issue 3: JSON parsing error in Postman
Error: Cannot deserialize
Solution:
‚Ä¢	Check JSON syntax (proper quotes, commas)
‚Ä¢	Verify Content-Type header: application/json
‚Ä¢	Ensure field names match Student class
Issue 4: Data disappears after restart
Solution:
‚Ä¢	This is expected (in-memory storage)
‚Ä¢	Data is stored in ArrayList, lost on restart
‚Ä¢	For persistence, use database
